  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Free to explore, pupils form their own cognition (\"mental meat\", in: Montessori, 2023.",
    "67) through their dynamic interaction with the environment.",
    "Therefore, they are taught indirectly, through their material engagement with their learning space, the classroom.",
    "Known as \"prepared environment\", the classroom is an immersive 'ecology' of purposefully selected and organised artefacts that allows students of different age and developmental stages (classes are age mixed, usually 1 st to 3 rd or 1 st to 6 th grade, and so on) to extrapolate knowledge from everyday activities, and multiple times at different levels of development (Lillard, 2021; Montessori, 1996a; 1996b; Ahlquist, 2023).",
    "Furniture, objects, and materials, all of the correct size and weight such that children can effectively interact with them (e.g., Frierson, 2022; Lillard, 2017; Saha, & Adhikari, 2023a; 2023b; Campos et al., 2018), are purposedly organised in the space tailoring interests and developmental trajectory of each child (Özerem & Kavas, 2013; Jensen, 2004; Okuo, 2014; Cuevas, 1997; Maldonado & Winick, 2003)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Known as \"prepared environment\", the classroom is an immersive 'ecology' of purposefully selected and organised artefacts that allows students of different age and developmental stages (classes are age mixed, usually 1 st to 3 rd or 1 st to 6 th grade, and so on) to extrapolate knowledge from everyday activities, and multiple times at different levels of development (Lillard, 2021; Montessori, 1996a; 1996b; Ahlquist, 2023).",
    "Furniture, objects, and materials, all of the correct size and weight such that children can effectively interact with them (e.g., Frierson, 2022; Lillard, 2017; Saha, & Adhikari, 2023a; 2023b; Campos et al., 2018), are purposedly organised in the space tailoring interests and developmental trajectory of each child (Özerem & Kavas, 2013; Jensen, 2004; Okuo, 2014; Cuevas, 1997; Maldonado & Winick, 2003)."
